Astronomy Picture of the Day
============================

[Discover the cosmos!](archivepix.html)
Each day a different image or photograph of our fascinating universe is
featured, along with a brief explanation written by a professional astronomer.

2006 January 21
  

[![See Explanation.  Clicking on the picture will download
 the highest resolution version available.](image/0601/bean_conrad_c70.jpg)](image/0601/bean_conrad_full.jpg)




 **Apollo 12: Self-Portrait**    

 **Credit:** 
Charles Conrad,
[Apollo 12](http://www-pao.ksc.nasa.gov/kscpao/history/apollo/apollo-12/
apollo-12.htm),
[NASA](http://www.nasa.gov/home/index.html)

 **Explanation:** 
In November of 1969,
[Apollo 12](ap990408.html) astronaut-photographer
[Charles "Pete" Conrad](ap990715.html) recorded
this masterpiece while documenting colleague
[Alan Bean's](http://www.alanbeangallery.com/)
lunar soil collection activities on the
[Oceanus Procellarum](http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/planet_volcano/
lunar/mare/mlm.html).
The image is [dramatic and stark](ap031109.html).
The harsh environment of the Moon's Ocean of Storms is
echoed in Bean's helmet, a perfectly
[composed
reflection](http://mirrorproject.com/galleries/gantz/) of Conrad and
[the
lunar horizon](http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/alsj/).
Is it art?
Works of photojournalists originally
intent on recording the human condition on planet Earth,
such as [Lewis W. Hine's](http://www.geh.org/fm/lwhprints/htmlsrc2/
index.html) images from New York City
in the early 20th century, or
[Margaret
Bourke-White's](http://lkwdpl.org/wihohio/bour-mar.htm) magazine photography are widely
regarded as art.
Similarly many documentary astronomy and
[space images](http://photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov)
can be appreciated for their artistic and
[esthetic appeal](http://heritage.stsci.edu/).

Astronomy Picture of the Day
============================

[Discover the cosmos!](archivepix.html)
Each day a different image or photograph of our fascinating universe is
featured, along with a brief explanation written by a professional astronomer.

2006 January 21
  

[![See Explanation.  Clicking on the picture will download
 the highest resolution version available.](image/0601/bean_conrad_c70.jpg)](image/0601/bean_conrad_full.jpg)




 **Apollo 12: Self-Portrait**    

 **Credit:** 
Charles Conrad,
[Apollo 12](http://www-pao.ksc.nasa.gov/kscpao/history/apollo/apollo-12/
apollo-12.htm),
[NASA](http://www.nasa.gov/home/index.html)

 **Explanation:** 
In November of 1969,
[Apollo 12](ap990408.html) astronaut-photographer
[Charles "Pete" Conrad](ap990715.html) recorded
this masterpiece while documenting colleague
[Alan Bean's](http://www.alanbeangallery.com/)
lunar soil collection activities on the
[Oceanus Procellarum](http://volcano.und.nodak.edu/vwdocs/planet_volcano/
lunar/mare/mlm.html).
The image is [dramatic and stark](ap031109.html).
The harsh environment of the Moon's Ocean of Storms is
echoed in Bean's helmet, a perfectly
[composed
reflection](http://mirrorproject.com/galleries/gantz/) of Conrad and
[the
lunar horizon](http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/pao/History/alsj/).
Is it art?
Works of photojournalists originally
intent on recording the human condition on planet Earth,
such as [Lewis W. Hine's](http://www.geh.org/fm/lwhprints/htmlsrc2/
index.html) images from New York City
in the early 20th century, or
[Margaret
Bourke-White's](http://lkwdpl.org/wihohio/bour-mar.htm) magazine photography are widely
regarded as art.
Similarly many documentary astronomy and
[space images](http://photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov)
can be appreciated for their artistic and
[esthetic appeal](http://heritage.stsci.edu/).
